{"/service/ndnp/uuml/batch_uuml_kirilenko_ver01/data/sn93062856/206534680/1907121401/0405.xml":{"full_text":"g\nI 1 J\nj T THE rcFTtRMOUlTTAIN AND COLORADO CATHOLIC DECEMBER 14 1907\n0\nP\nili\n1 fl c\nESTABLISHED 1899\nk F THE COLORADO CATHOLIC\n1\nESTABLISHED 1884\n4 CONSOLIDATED OCTOBER 2 1899\nL\nj\nI 200 A YEAR IN ADVANCE\nPublished Every Saturday by the Intermountain\nI Catholic Publishing Company 424 Atlas Block West\nSecond South Salt Lake City Utah Telephone 567\nj\nREMITTANCES\nRemittances should be made by postofflce or ex\npress money orders drafts or registered letters\nCHANGING ADDRESSES\nSubscribers removing from one place to another\nand desiring papers changed should always give for\nf mer as well as present address\nr\ni CORRESPONDENCE SOLICITED\nThe Reverend Clergy are requested to send to THE\nINTERMOUNTAIN CATHOLIC news contributions\ni of Interest to their respective parishes\nEntered in the Postofilce at Salt Lake as Second\nClass Matter\nCARD FROM BISHOP SCANLAN\nI feel it my duty to protect Catholics and the pub\nt lic generally from fraud and Imposition by notifying\nthem from time to time that no person bearing the\nname and garb of a priest or sister or anyone else Is\nauthorized or permitted to solicit or collect In this\nI diocese ror any purpose whatever connected with tha\nCatholic Chuch without having from mo permission\nin writing bearing my seal and signature Should\nanyone be found engaged in doing this unlawful\nwork or collecting without such a document he or\nshe as the case may be should be regarded by all as\na fraud and an imposter L SCANLAN\nBishop of Salt Lake\ni\nTO OUR SUBSCRIBERS\nThe Intermountain Catholic goes into nearly every\nCatholic home in this diocese Its circulation in Mon\ntana Idaho Colorado Wyoming Nevada and many\nother states is very large Only reliable firms and\nbusiness men advertise in the paper All subscribers\nwill find It to their advantage when about to invest\npurchase or consult on business matters to read over\nthe list of our advertisers We not only recommend\nbut ask for them the patronage of all our readers\nI t\nThe onset of winter seems to have put the immunity\nI I\ni munity bath out of business\nWell the fleet is 011 the way to the Pacific and\nI II I\nn war hasnt been declared yet\nIt is about time for Secretary Root to blame\nI I\nHearst for the financial panic\nI I Talk is cheap but congress maintains an ex\nII pensive reputation with money talks\nI I Well if the weather hasnt suited you lately\nJ I just remember that Chicago is still on the map\nI I With a 30000word message it may be said that\nc the price of paper hasnt discouraged the president\nIt will be observed that there is no lack of bills\nI I left in congress to reform what little currency there is\nHowever the presumption is in favor of the ex\nI f I placed istence of Santa Claus if your heart is not mis\nNext t time prosperity wings its flight in our\nI\nI 1 direction we will put a little salt on its tail if we\ni i can get the salt I\nHowever there is comfort in the thought that\nI il congress doesnt know what to do with the financial\nI situation eIther\nWhat was the meekest and humblest event of\nI uli li 1 universal history Almighty God the Creator dy\nr ing on S cross between two thieves\nI We have not yet heard whether Mars is Demo\nI r J cratic or Republican Here is a good opportunity\nt for a bright reporter to score a beat\nr It would be unfair to try to read between the\nI lines of that 30000word message there being suf\neient for all purposes without doing so\nNo soul will be lost that can stand before a\nI 1 stablehorn God and say I never refused hungry\njuan food and never publicly boasted of it\nt 1 Probably it was to supply the increased demand\nI for water which will come with prohibition that\nJ\n1 Atlanta has put in a pump at a cost of 135000\nr Poor Los happy hunting ground has been dis\nt covered It is among the gullible who like to be\nI f11 fleeced through the medium which he controls at\n1 the spiritualistic Seance\nJ i Some statisticians heartless\naro Heres one\nI who has figured out that Italy can be converted to\nMethodism in 13000 years Certainly there is\nmadness in their methods\nr Maybe the reformed I methods of accounting\nI in Salt Lakes public affairs are intended to make\na better showing when the census bureau gets out\n8 another volume of statistics of cities\nRemember when you are celebrating Christmas\nthat the name is derived from a union of Gods\nI Messiaical name with the Catholic mass And\nthis union is a wonderful thing in our eyes\nChristmas presents which are a reminder of the\ncause for the celebration of the day are eminently\nof more value and appropriateness than something\nboth pretty and useful though not possessing this\none requisite As a suggestion if the suggestion I\nwill be pardoned for an appropriate Christmas I\npresent we submit as of the highest order a subscription\nI\nscription to this paper\nA new kind of automobile is said to be making\na great hit with the public Poor public\nThat information may finally penetrate into\neven the United States senate is shown by the dis\ncovery by a senate committee that the Indian is be\ning robbed\na\nNevertheless Andy Carnegie did some pretty\ngood work in founding libraries in so many towns\nand cities We hope he will see this and send us\na Christmas present\n1 Co\nSome men are so foolish they imagine they will\nsee Jack Rockefeller making little ones into big\nones or big rocks into smaller ones but Jack doesnt\nhandle that kind of rocks\nDemand is made by a New York hospital for\n600 additional beds for alcoholic patients but then\nthe saloons are a beneficent institution and produce\nmuch revenue and misery\nWill some kindly spiritist tell us what the\nghost of Darwin thinks about the origin of spe\ncies by this time It certainly must believe in the\nmonkey shines of the spiritists themselves\nIt is not so very long ago since all our maga\nzines were full of the doings of Captains of In\ndustry and now many of our jails are full of their\ndoings in the brush rooms and on the rock piles\nIe\nSwarthmore college having declined a 3000000\ndonation made with the proviso that athletics be\nabolished in the institution evidences more respect\nfor itself than for the value of either the money\nor the sport\n0 I\nWere you ever so poor that you or your children\nhad to be given birth in a stable and yet we are\nabout to celebrate the birthday of God who re\ndeemed the world by an humble birth and dreadful\ndeath Why should any one be proud l\nThe financial panic sent a few rich men to\ntheir graves and that by their own hands Free\nwill is a terrible instrument in the power of us\nall A little patience and those foolish millionaires\nmight have found life worth living in soothing the\nsorrows of others\nI\nIn Salt Lake City recently because of sin a\nyoung girl sought and found an untimely grave\nand those who helped by their licentiousness to\nshovel the clay over her dead body before her time\ndid not believe in Christ heaven and hell But\nthey will have to aSiswer an angry God in the day\nof retributive justice\n11\nThe editor of a secular newspaper needs to save\nhis soul just as much as the poorest vagabond\nand more so as he has a life filled with less sor\nrows than the wanderer and the toiling laborer\nTemporal positions and distinctions do not exist\nin eternity Hell may be full of editors and heaven\nwell crowded with paupers\nI\nWhat has become of that old joke which as\nserted that an employe should not watch the clock\nbut toil on and on for the success of his employer\nif he wished to succeed It certainly was a good\njoke while it lasted even if it did make thousands\nof men hot who had worked faithfully for twenty\nyears without receiving any promotion or increase\nin pay\nII\nIf you believe in Christ that he is God and you\nare an employer of men you should for His sake\npay them salaries as high as you can reasonably\nafford Christ despises the man of means who pays\nas low as he possibly can to his workingmen Treat\nyour employes justly and Gods blessing will be on\nyou Do the reverse and Gods curse will follow\nyou and yours\nTHE GOLDFIELD TROUBLE\nThe Goldfield labor situation is one that calls\nfor the utmost coolness and selfcontrol on the\npart of both miners and mine owners The mem\nbers of the mine owners association recite a list of\nwrongs at the hands of their employes which if\ntrue more than justifies their desire for a change\nOf the charges that of open looting of the high\ngrade mines is the most serious Even though the\ngold may seem by the miners to have been placed\nin the earth by the bounty of God equally for all\nmens use it is only our social organization that\ngives it any value and the miners as lawful mem\nbers of society and servants of their employers\nhave not a shadow of right to carry the gold away\nSpread of the socialist doctrines among the West\nern Federation has done much to weaken the good\noldfashioned ideas of morality and right\nOn the other hand the miners assert that it is\nthe owners who have precipitated a fight who\nhave induced Governor Sparks to ask for United\nStates troops who have determined to drive the\nWestern Federation of Miners from Goldfield and\nNevada and who will alone be responsible for\nany trouble that may occur\nOf course there will be no fight unless the mi\nners fight and they will not fight except in defense\nof what they conceive to be their rights If among\nthose rights they include\nhighgrading they are\nif merely to for the\nwrong organize peaceable reg\nulation of wages and conditions of labor they are\nright Equally the employers right to employ\nwhomsoever they will cannot be\nI denied so long as\na faithfully kept contract does not prohibit\nSo it appears that endless bickering and trouble\nand even bloodshed may result at Goldfield unless\nthe matters at issue i between operators and the fed I\neration be speedily adjusted Undoubtedly there is\naot L\nright upon both sides and a plentiful proportion\nof wrong There is no hope of a settlement with\nout the putting aside of passions and prejudices on\nboth sides which can only become more bitter as the\nstruggle is prolonged\nIt is devoutly to be hoped that a compromise\nmay be reached and that soon Otherwise the\nprospects for one or both of the parties and for\nNevada and even for other mining districts where\nthe Western Federation has been active can hardly\nbe regarded as anything but gloomy\nWHATS THE MATTER WITH SALT LAKE\nThe bureau of the census of the department of\ncommerce and labor has undertaken the enormous\ntask of collecting statistics of the various cities\nof the country and the result of the third effort is\na book of about 400 pages entitled Statistics of\nCities Having a Population of Over 30000 1005\nBefore the census bureau took up this task sev\neral years ago there was no statistical information\navailable by which the progress of cities could be\ncompared and if a comparison will stir to emula\ntion of the more progressive all those cities which\nhave fallen short there is a broad and sufficient\njustification for the expense attaching to the col\nlection and publication of the data\nMunicipal problems arc very similar in different\ntowns The people must cope with an outworn\npartisan political system of government and ef\nficiency and economy in one department very\ngenerally offset by inefficiency in another so that\nnet results of the administration of the various\ncities business in some cases do not show wherein\none has outstripped another to any startling de\ngree Fortunate however is the city whose citi\nzens will study the figures and by comparison force\nhome upon these administrations the points where\nin other towns excel and spur them on to an emu\nlation of the more worthy Better results must\nfollow\nI There arc 154 cities in the nation with 30000\nor more population divided in the report into four\ngroups The first group those cities having a pop\nulation of 300000 and over contains 15 cities Cities\nof 100000 to 300000 make group two which con\ntains 25 cities Group three cities of 50000 to\n100000 contains 47 cities in which group Salt\nLake appears as No 75 Group four has 67 cities\nhaving a population of 30000 to 50000\nIn comparison with other cities of about the\nCOTVQ T l Salt Lakes i\nsame population s showing in some re\nspects is very favorable In some other respects\nthe report shows a woeful deficiency The area of\nSalt Lake is 29758 acres which is greater than that\nof Boston Baltimore Cleveland Buffalo Pittsburg\nCincinnati or Detroit which cities have popula\ntions of from 600000 down to 325000 Salt Lake\nhas 120 acres of parks inside the city limits and 50\nacres outside The city also has 45 acres of play\ngrounds In these two respects comparison with\nothers of approximately the same population is not\nunfavorable\nIf we are to judge from the statistics of the po\nlice departments Salt Lake had either a remark\nably efficient force or a remarkably wicked popu\nlation With 38 patrolmen which is far less than\nthe average for cities of group three Utica N Y\nand Waterbury Conn having 37 and 36 respec\ntively being the only cities in the group with few\ner patrolmen Salt Lake is credited with 4619 ar\nrests for all offenses Only 14 other cities of group\nthree 47 cities had more arrests than Salt Lake\nDrunkenness and disturbing the peace are very\nlargely causes of arrest and in these two things\nSalt Lake is not especially preeminent\nHomicide was the cause of 22 arrests in Salt\nLake In this delectable pastime Salt Lakers have\noutdone the people of every other city in the\ngroup and only fourteen other cities of the na\ntion stand above her Of these all but one Bir\nmingham Ala with 109 arrests for homicide are\nvery much larger cities There were 427 arrests\nfor gambling Only ten cities of the nation had\nniore The social evil was the cause of 1045\narrests In this respect Salt Lake is the eighih\ncity of the nation trotting in the same class with\nNew York Chicago Philadelphia St Louis Pitts\nburg Kansas City Mo and Des Moines\nIn the matter of paved streets it should be re\nmembered these figures are for 1905 Salt Lake was\nin a class almost by itself with a grand total of 7\nmiles 22 of which was granite block and 48 as\nphalt Of the 154 cities with a population of 30\n000 or over there were just five cities with less\npaved streets than Salt Lake Spokane 41 miles\nButte 26 South Omaha 69 Macon 65 Pueblo\n14\nFinancial operations show that only 13 of the 47\ncities of group three had larger gross incomes\nthan Salt Lake 3089688 The portion accredited\nto city government was 2580603 there being\nonly eleven cities in the group with larger amounts\nSchools are credited with 487323 and only ten\ncities in the group had more money to spend on\nthe public schools\nExpenses for general government aggregated\n97117 with nine cities in the group greater the\nper capita being 165 the highest in the group\nthe average being 92 cents Only seven cities New\nYork 236 Philadelphia 178 St Louis 183\nBoston 382 Denver 385 Syracuse 168 New\nton Mass 211 have\nass higher\na per capita ex\npense for general government\nSalt Lake had 56 miles of all classes of sewers in\nin 1905 Only ten cities of the group had less\nWhereas Pueblo city No 152 had only 14 miles\nof paved streets the town had\n1111 miles of sew\ners which fact compensates some for Pueblo but\nmakes Salt Lakes showing only more deficient\nThere are a great many other things in the book\nover which the student of statistics will doubtless\nreflect For instance the per capita debt obliga\ntions less sinking fund assets for Salt Lake was\nt\n8020 Only ten of the 154 cities reported had a\nlarger per capita debt obligation And the total\nper capita corporate receipts of Salt Lake were\n4693 which with the exception of Boston 5232\nand Spokane 5712 was the largest in the coun\ntry The municipal economist may be able to ex\nplain these thingsthese 7 miles of paved streets\n56 miles of sewers the third to the largest per cap\nita receipts of any city in the country the eleventh\nplace from the top in per capita debt obligations\nwe say the municipal economist may be blc to ex\nplain these things by some law of thriftiness with\nwhich we are not acquainted but until that expla\nnation is forthcoming we shall view the statistics\nwith astonishment\nThe value of the G statistics will never ho\nknown unless they be given thoughtful study Wo\nrecommend the book to the citizens of Salt Lake\nas an invaluable contribution to the campaign for\na commission system of government On the face\nof the figures there seems to be something wrong\nc\nTHE IRISH PARLIAMENTARY PARTY\nThere is in Ireland at the present time an organ\nization contending with Mr John Redmond and his\nfollowers as to what policy shall be pursued regard\ning the fight for home rule That there may hon\nestly exist differences of opinion among politicians\nin any nation and on any policy is not refutable\nbut in the light of all its past and glorious history I\nno man can honestly antagonize the Irish Parlia\nmentary party Ever since that memorable day\nwhen Legislator Daniel OConnell the Liberator\nstood heroically before the speaker of the house of\ncommons and Spartanlike defied the mighty em\npire of Great Britain the Irish representatives in\nLondon have done valiant deeds\nBefore the illuminating flames of OConnellt\neloquent utterance for common justice there sprang\ninto being instantly and magically emancipation\nfor Gods and Erins indestructible and faithful I I I\nchurch of Rome and no man can fully measure the\nconsequent blessings that have flowed like pure rills\nof sparkling water throughout other portions of the\nworld to refresh famishing humanity from that\nglorious fountain sent gushing from the barren\nrock of English folly by the noblest Irish Roman\nof them all OConnell is sleeping in his grave\nthe sleep of the just and his deeds live after him\nimperishable monuments of his fame his genius\nand his Irish manhood Yet there were not want\ning foolish sons of Erin who helped by their acts\nand utterances to break OConnells heart that gi\ngantic heart of Irish oak that wept like a child\nand suffered shocks and beat them back as Gib\nralter hurls majestically from it the proud swelling l\ning waves of the sea Could we find space to tell\nof all the wondrous deeds of brave Irish Parlia\nmentarians in London how many an Homeric bal\nlad would unfold to the world\nCharles Stuart Parnell Protestant was another\ncourageous manly eloquent general of the Irish\nlegislative gladiators which small body under his\nwise leadership stood mentally and physically as\nresolute in the defense of justice as did the Gre\ncian heroes at Thermopylae\nMany there were to be sure who threw stones at\nParnell when scandal threatened him forgetting\ntheir own crimes and seeking to palliate them by\npublicly denouncing the Irish leader Parnell needs\nno defense With the exception of one accusation\nnever satisfactorily proven his life was an inspiring\none In our own times we observe new soldiers in\nthe holy cause of liberty under the masterly lead\nership of JohnRedmond fighting invincibly for their\nrights as did their ancestors on every honorable\nfield manifesting the unconquerable spirit of Pat\nrick Sarsfield and his iron warriors of Limerick\nWe see Ireland slowly but surely acquiring the\nlands under the new land act Had the Liberal\nparty kept faith Redmond could even now boast\nthat captivating glory of giving to Erin home\nrule Look too at the s 1fgo ernment of Irish\nmunicipalities The isle of heroes saints and mar\ntyrs is doing as well as can bo anticipated in the\nface of long ages of British prejudice which can\nnot be destroyed in a day\nThe men then under whatever name they hoist\nthe skull and crossbones of anarchical and piratical\nopposition to the Irish party in the house of com\nmons should everywhere be castigated and repre\nhended There is no other way under heaven except\nby force always in the past unfortunate and suici\ndal to Erins hopes by which anything important\nn x a J UO uupiM tuitk\ncan be attained than by the present system of Irish\nrepresentation in London The men of this body\nare the sentinels to preserve the achievements of\nthe past and to acquire new ones in the future\nLet every true Irishman cry dom the mis\nguided efforts of factionists even though patriotic\nin intention they undoubtedly are They tend to\ndestroy not build up They cause disgust at home\nand abroad They are worse enemies of their coun\ntry did they butrealize it than bigoted English\nmen They give substance and support to the as\nsertion that Irishmen cannot agree among them\nselves It is a shortsighted policy they fQllow at\nbest They arc like founders of new sects who\nraise their intellects higher than Gods and the wis\ndom of the ages They assume that they know\nbest and that their opponents though in a large\nmajority are selfish ignorant and false Let them\nwait for the country to indorse them and until\nthat time they arc in duty bound to support those\nmen the Irish nation has indorsed No country\nweak as Ireland at least in modern times can gain\nanything by coercion On the fields of thought\nand controversy are victories won today A united\nbody legally empowered to act battling shoulder to\nshoulder for justice in the legislative halls of Eng\nland is the only way The past proves it the pres\nent confirms it and the future will see Irelands\nhopes in full fruition Away with the wrangling\nfactionists and their novel and individual ideas\nThey have always I been the enemies of\naN\nprogress\nThey batten on contention and grw r I n\ntism They arc men who spurn authorIty n ri hn\nand state all wishing to be officers ant\n1PT1 1 n\nserve in the ranks They deserve thr nn n\n3 3j\ncasm and ridicule of mankind Let nr i P\nof Erin give countenance to the p h\nw h\nin sheeps clothing who bark but arc t\nVdr\nto bite\nTHE HOODLUM ELEMENT\nThe clever and versatile editor of t\nt Ld\nTelegramtaking his text from the u 1 i lit\nnolieeman who to save his own life 1\na Salt Lake thughas a very vigorn\nful leader on the tougher element in on t\nI\nGoodwin is of the opinion that Societ f v I t\nIJ\nbj in selfdefense take from their h u tllp\nilr of vicious or too indulgent pal t J fj\ntheir lies into different channels ami\nan I 4r t\nneeded discipline Further on in hn artiJp b\nsuggests that A military camp under rhn mt\nof kind and firm officers is the best In I L f\nsuch children\nThe admission of the writer that i fr t d\nfailed to control the acquired or inherit i pnd rc\nto savagery in some of our young poplP I3\nrather dismal reflection on our Sunday hr j\nclasses and public schools It is a candi acting\ncdgment on the part of the writer that with all flj I\nhigh and public school ha oj\ntraining we have mt\nsucceeded in controlling or indeed\no impring\ningti t\nvulgarity and viciousness so painfullj mtierable\nthe daily conduct of of our hrv\nmany young hovs arJ\ngirls Mr Goodwin recommends the cstahlisshm\nof military camps for these incorrigabk hut\nreflection he will be satisfied that his upgest r\nwhile theoretically attractive would in practjcp c\nfraught with serious if not insurmountable Lv\nculties Already our people are contributing j t\nnually for the support of our public schools 1\nschools academics colleges universities\nand\npr\nvate educational institutions something likf t\nhundred millions a year Enough to dig twc Pa\nama canals To maintain our prisons jail a\nlums penitentiaries and reformatories\nto say n\ning of our police and detective departmenfs iP\nexpend four hundred\nmillions every year\n1Vhen the military camps which Mr jfttl\nadvocates in good faith\nare established a\nequipped and the young toughs gathered in wi\nare we to do with the vast dependent multitude\ndefectives and degenerates so rapidly multipl\nin our country What should be the attitude of ti\nstate toward them l Should their lives be guam\ned and their movements governed l Must the Qta K\nsay to each one of them My child your life ha\nbeen one succession of failures\nYou cannot PO\nduct yourself decently You\ncannot control ynr\nappetites and passions Left to\nyourself you a7\nnot only useless but mischievous l\nyou are and\na mp\nnacc to your fellow men I have tried schooling\npunishing reforming you and I have failed YJT1\nare an incurable a degenerate a being unfit fi f\nfreedom for social life I will feed and clothe\nyou and give you a reasonably comfortable life\nOne thing I will not allow\nyou to doyou oann\nprocreate your kind You shall bo the\nlast of VU\nfeeble and degenerate family\nThen having erected the carn sand thC hnmt\nfor defectives who is to pronoirnce on the dpge\neracy for admission to these instUutions Woul\nMr Goodwin include among the h drums the iff\nbeciles the degenerates and the deleaves the hign\nschool boys who the other day force the doors r\none of our theatres and stampeded th\nwomen ar\nchildren with the cry of fire I fire on the twcn\nodd members of the high school foothill I team r\nbaseball club who entered a street car no\nnolong atr\nconducted themselves shamefully and i\ninalted an\nunprotected lady Would he sentence to rse in\nstitutions the thirty boys and girls summ d DO\nlong ago before the juvenile court of this ty fl\ngrossly immoral and indecent actions in one 011\nparks or the university graduates who p ie\nburlesqued and profaned the sanctity of an rA\nWho is to haw the line and where is i it t\ndrawn\nThe tramp or the hoodlum of the lower sta\nof society is a growth an accident but the XP\ndressed school rowdy is the manufactured attic\nfinished marketed and labeled Fit for decen\nsociety J And here let it be whispered that tt t\nstate and 1 i r f\na society have more to fear from thC ma\nufactured hoodlum article than from the tramp or tb at I\nDEATH OF ST JOSEPH\nEliza Allen Starr\nThe Patriarch Joseph fosterfather mild\nOf Nazareths VirginMothers heavenly chl7d\nHis dying head pressed close against the Il1EP\nOf the Incarnate Son and Diety\nThe VirginMother kneeling gently near\nDissolved in prayer on that mild cheek a tear\nThus has the Christian Masters pious mind\nThe Just Mans death designed\nThe picture breathing all the holy peace\nOf souls which find in death from death release\nThus placed a wish long cherished found rxprp3\nsion\nWhen I shall come to my deathbed confession\nWhen faithful priest shall that last unction give\nWhich bids these lapsing dying senses live\nOn Gods own day of happy resurrection\nAs longtried l vessels of most sweet election\nWhen on my parched enfeebled tongue shall lie\nJesus Himself in loving mystery\nThen my three friends in fair celestial statE\nUnseen around my bed benignly wait\nThus shall I win while yielding up my breath\nLifes last and crowning grace a happy death\nO Jesus Mary Joseph me befriend j\nWhen this so troubled life begins to end\n0 Jesus Mary Joseph I with you near\nDeaths dreaded spectres all will disappear\nAnd though no friend may come with pious arS\nTo wipe the deathsweat lift the last sweet pralt\nContentedly serenely I can die\nIn your most dear and holy company","height":"24816","width":"19161"}}
